     {q:"Why might an integral be considered improper if its integrand becomes unbounded (approaches infinity) within the interval?", options:["The function’s value grows without limit at some point, requiring special evaluation using a limit","This concept has no connection to how integrals are classified","An unbounded integrand has no effect on how an integral should be evaluated","Improper integrals never involve any unbounded behaviour within the interval"], answer:0},
     {q:"Why are improper integrals useful for modelling real-world situations, such as calculating total probability over an infinite range of outcomes?", options:["This concept only applies to purely abstract, theoretical mathematics","Improper integrals have no real-world modelling applications","They provide a mathematical framework for handling quantities that extend over an infinite interval","Infinite intervals can never be meaningfully evaluated using integration"], answer:2}
