     {q:"Euler’s Method uses small, successive ___ based on the equation’s slope at each point.", options:["Random, unrelated jumps with no mathematical basis","Steps determined entirely by guesswork with no calculation involved","Linear steps","A concept unrelated to slope or rate of change"], answer:2},
     {q:"Why might Euler’s Method be useful for differential equations that cannot be solved using standard analytical techniques?", options:["All differential equations can always be solved exactly using simple algebraic methods","This concept has no connection to approximating solutions numerically","It provides a practical way to approximate a solution numerically, even when an exact algebraic solution is difficult to find","Euler’s Method is never useful for solving any type of differential equation"], answer:2},
     {q:"Why does using smaller step sizes generally improve the accuracy of Euler’s Method?", options:["Step size has no effect on the accuracy of Euler’s Method","Smaller step sizes always make the approximation significantly less accurate","Smaller steps more closely follow the true curve of the solution, reducing the accumulated approximation error","This concept has no connection to how numerical approximation methods work"], answer:2},
     {q:"Why are numerical methods like Euler’s Method important in fields like engineering and physics, where exact solutions are often unavailable?", options:["They provide a practical, computable way to model and predict system behaviour despite the complexity of the underlying equations","Numerical methods have no real-world application in engineering or physics","Engineers and physicists never need to work with equations that lack exact solutions","This concept only applies to purely theoretical mathematics with no practical use"], answer:0}
