     {q:"Why is a standard analog clock often used as an everyday example of modular arithmetic?", options:["This concept has no relevance to understanding modular systems","A clock has no connection to how modular arithmetic functions","The hours wrap back around to 1 after reaching 12, mirroring how modular arithmetic wraps around after reaching the modulus","Clocks always count upward with no repeating or wrapping pattern"], answer:2},
     {q:"Why is modular arithmetic considered essential to modern cryptographic systems that protect digital information?", options:["Many encryption methods rely on the mathematical properties of numbers within a modular system to securely encode and decode information","Modular arithmetic has no connection to how digital information is secured","This concept has no relevance to digital security or encryption","Cryptography never relies on any mathematical structure or system"], answer:0}
